events.description: Thutmose III ascends to the throne of Egypt, although power effectively shifts to Hatshepsut (according to the Low Chronology of the 18th dynasty).
events.html: • 1479 BC – Thutmose III ascends to the throne of Egypt, although power effectively shifts to Hatshepsut (according to the Low Chronology of the 18th dynasty).

events.description: Traditional reckoning of the Fall of Troy marking the end of the legendary Trojan War, given by chief librarian of the Library of Alexandria Eratosthenes, among others.
events.html: • 1183 BC – Traditional reckoning of the Fall of Troy marking the end of the legendary Trojan War, given by chief librarian of the Library of Alexandria Eratosthenes, among others.[1]

events.description: Battle of Mühlberg. Duke of Alba, commanding Spanish-Imperial forces of Charles I of Spain, defeats the troops of Schmalkaldic League.
events.html: • 1547 – Battle of Mühlberg. Duke of Alba, commanding Spanish-Imperial forces of Charles I of Spain, defeats the troops of Schmalkaldic League.

entities.name: Fernando Álvarez de Toledo, 3rd Duke of Alba

events.description: Mary, Queen of Scots, marries the Dauphin of France, François, at Notre-Dame de Paris.
events.html: • 1558 – Mary, Queen of Scots, marries the Dauphin of France, François, at Notre-Dame de Paris.[2]

entities.name: Wedding of Mary, Queen of Scots, and Francis, Dauphin of France

events.description: The first regular newspaper in British Colonial America, The Boston News-Letter, is published.
events.html: • 1704 – The first regular newspaper in British Colonial America, The Boston News-Letter, is published.

events.description: French revolutionary Jean-Paul Marat is acquitted by the Revolutionary Tribunal of charges brought by the Girondin in Paris.
events.html: • 1793 – French revolutionary Jean-Paul Marat is acquitted by the Revolutionary Tribunal of charges brought by the Girondin in Paris.[3]

events.description: The United States Library of Congress is established when President John Adams signs legislation to appropriate $5,000 to purchase "such books as may be necessary for the use of Congress".
events.html: • 1800 – The United States Library of Congress is established when President John Adams signs legislation to appropriate $5,000 to purchase "such books as may be necessary for the use of Congress".

events.description: The great fire in Surat city of India caused more than 500 deaths and destruction of more than 9,000 houses.
events.html: • 1837 – The great fire in Surat city of India caused more than 500 deaths and destruction of more than 9,000 houses.[4]

events.description: Russo-Turkish War: Russian Empire declares war on Ottoman Empire.
events.html: • 1877 – Russo-Turkish War: Russian Empire declares war on Ottoman Empire.

events.description: American sharpshooter Annie Oakley is hired by Nate Salsbury to be a part of Buffalo Bill's Wild West.
events.html: • 1885 – American sharpshooter Annie Oakley is hired by Nate Salsbury to be a part of Buffalo Bill's Wild West.

events.description: Joshua Slocum, the first person to sail single-handedly around the world, sets sail from Boston, Massachusetts aboard the sloop Spray.
events.html: • 1895 – Joshua Slocum, the first person to sail single-handedly around the world, sets sail from Boston, Massachusetts aboard the sloop Spray.

events.description: The Woolworth Building, a skyscraper in New York City, is opened.
events.html: • 1913 – The Woolworth Building, a skyscraper in New York City, is opened.

events.description: The Franck–Hertz experiment, a pillar of quantum mechanics, is presented to the German Physical Society.
events.html: • 1914 – The Franck–Hertz experiment, a pillar of quantum mechanics, is presented to the German Physical Society.

events.description: The arrest of 250 Armenian intellectuals and community leaders in Istanbul marks the beginning of the Armenian genocide.
events.html: • 1915 – The arrest of 250 Armenian intellectuals and community leaders in Istanbul marks the beginning of the Armenian genocide.

entities.name: Deportation of Armenian intellectuals on 24 April 1915

events.description: Easter Rising: Irish rebels, led by Patrick Pearse and James Connolly, launch an uprising in Dublin against British rule and proclaim an Irish Republic.
events.html: • 1916 – Easter Rising: Irish rebels, led by Patrick Pearse and James Connolly, launch an uprising in Dublin against British rule and proclaim an Irish Republic.

events.description: Ernest Shackleton and five men of the Imperial Trans-Antarctic Expedition launch a lifeboat from uninhabited Elephant Island in the Southern Ocean to organise a rescue for the crew of the sunken Endurance.
events.html: • 1916 – Ernest Shackleton and five men of the Imperial Trans-Antarctic Expedition launch a lifeboat from uninhabited Elephant Island in the Southern Ocean to organise a rescue for the crew of the sunken Endurance.

events.description: World War I: First tank-to-tank combat, during the second Battle of Villers-Bretonneux. Three British Mark IVs meet three German A7Vs.
events.html: • 1918 – World War I: First tank-to-tank combat, during the second Battle of Villers-Bretonneux. Three British Mark IVs meet three German A7Vs.

events.description: The first segment of the Imperial Wireless Chain providing wireless telegraphy between Leafield in Oxfordshire, England, and Cairo, Egypt, comes into operation.
events.html: • 1922 – The first segment of the Imperial Wireless Chain providing wireless telegraphy between Leafield in Oxfordshire, England, and Cairo, Egypt, comes into operation.

events.description: Thorvald Stauning becomes premier of Denmark (first term).
events.html: • 1924 – Thorvald Stauning becomes premier of Denmark (first term).[5]

events.description: The Treaty of Berlin is signed. Germany and the Soviet Union each pledge neutrality in the event of an attack on the other by a third party for the next five years.
events.html: • 1926 – The Treaty of Berlin is signed. Germany and the Soviet Union each pledge neutrality in the event of an attack on the other by a third party for the next five years.

events.description: Benny Rothman leads the mass trespass of Kinder Scout, leading to substantial legal reforms in the United Kingdom.
events.html: • 1932 – Benny Rothman leads the mass trespass of Kinder Scout, leading to substantial legal reforms in the United Kingdom.

events.description: Nazi Germany begins its persecution of Jehovah's Witnesses by shutting down the Watch Tower Society office in Magdeburg.
events.html: • 1933 – Nazi Germany begins its persecution of Jehovah's Witnesses by shutting down the Watch Tower Society office in Magdeburg.

entities.name: Persecution of Jehovah's Witnesses in Nazi Germany

events.description: World War II: The SBS launches a raid against the garrison of Santorini in Greece.
events.html: • 1944 – World War II: The SBS launches a raid against the garrison of Santorini in Greece.

events.description: Winston Churchill is knighted by Queen Elizabeth II.
events.html: • 1953 – Winston Churchill is knighted by Queen Elizabeth II.

events.description: The Bandung Conference ends: Twenty-nine non-aligned nations of Asia and Africa finish a meeting that condemns colonialism, racism, and the Cold War.
events.html: • 1955 – The Bandung Conference ends: Twenty-nine non-aligned nations of Asia and Africa finish a meeting that condemns colonialism, racism, and the Cold War.

events.description: Suez Crisis: The Suez Canal is reopened following the introduction of UNEF peacekeepers to the region.
events.html: • 1957 – Suez Crisis: The Suez Canal is reopened following the introduction of UNEF peacekeepers to the region.

events.description: Marriage of Princess Alexandra of Kent to Angus Ogilvy at Westminster Abbey in London.
events.html: • 1963 – Marriage of Princess Alexandra of Kent to Angus Ogilvy at Westminster Abbey in London.

entities.name: Princess Alexandra, The Honourable Lady Ogilvy

events.description: Civil war breaks out in the Dominican Republic when Colonel Francisco Caamaño overthrows the triumvirate that had been in power since the coup d'état against Juan Bosch.
events.html: • 1965 – Civil war breaks out in the Dominican Republic when Colonel Francisco Caamaño overthrows the triumvirate that had been in power since the coup d'état against Juan Bosch.

events.description: Cosmonaut Vladimir Komarov dies in Soyuz 1 when its parachute fails to open. He is the first human to die during a space mission.
events.html: • 1967 – Cosmonaut Vladimir Komarov dies in Soyuz 1 when its parachute fails to open. He is the first human to die during a space mission.

events.description: Vietnam War: American General William Westmoreland says in a news conference that the enemy had "gained support in the United States that gives him hope that he can win politically that which he cannot win militarily".
events.html: • 1967 – Vietnam War: American General William Westmoreland says in a news conference that the enemy had "gained support in the United States that gives him hope that he can win politically that which he cannot win militarily".

events.description: China launches Dong Fang Hong I, becoming the fifth nation to put an object into orbit using its own booster.
events.html: • 1970 – China launches Dong Fang Hong I, becoming the fifth nation to put an object into orbit using its own booster.[6]

events.description: The Gambia becomes a republic within the Commonwealth of Nations, with Dawda Jawara as its first President.
events.html: • 1970 – The Gambia becomes a republic within the Commonwealth of Nations, with Dawda Jawara as its first President.

events.description: Blair Peach, a British activist, died after being knocked unconscious during an Anti-Nazi League demonstration against a National Front election meeting in Southall, London.
events.html: • 1979 – Blair Peach, a British activist, died after being knocked unconscious during an Anti-Nazi League demonstration against a National Front election meeting in Southall, London.[7]

events.description: Eight U.S. servicemen die in Operation Eagle Claw as they attempt to end the Iran hostage crisis.
events.html: • 1980 – Eight U.S. servicemen die in Operation Eagle Claw as they attempt to end the Iran hostage crisis.

events.description: STS-31: The Hubble Space Telescope is launched from the Space Shuttle Discovery.
events.html: • 1990 – STS-31: The Hubble Space Telescope is launched from the Space Shuttle Discovery.

events.description: Gruinard Island, Scotland, is officially declared free of the anthrax disease after 48 years of quarantine.
events.html: • 1990 – Gruinard Island, Scotland, is officially declared free of the anthrax disease after 48 years of quarantine.

events.description: An IRA bomb devastates the Bishopsgate area of London.
events.html: • 1993 – An IRA bomb devastates the Bishopsgate area of London.

events.description: A Douglas DC-3 ditches in Botany Bay after takeoff from Sydney Airport. All 25 people on board survive.
events.html: • 1994 – A Douglas DC-3 ditches in Botany Bay after takeoff from Sydney Airport. All 25 people on board survive.[8]

events.description: In the United States, the Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act of 1996 is passed into law.
events.html: • 1996 – In the United States, the Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act of 1996 is passed into law.

entities.name: Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act of 1996

events.description: The United States lifts economic sanctions imposed on Libya 18 years previously, as a reward for its cooperation in eliminating weapons of mass destruction.
events.html: • 2004 – The United States lifts economic sanctions imposed on Libya 18 years previously, as a reward for its cooperation in eliminating weapons of mass destruction.

entities.name: History of Libya under Muammar Gaddafi

events.description: Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger is inaugurated as the 265th Pope of the Catholic Church taking the name Pope Benedict XVI.
events.html: • 2005 – Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger is inaugurated as the 265th Pope of the Catholic Church taking the name Pope Benedict XVI.

events.description: Bombings in the Egyptian resort city of Dahab kill 23 people and injure about 80.
events.html: • 2006 – Bombings in the Egyptian resort city of Dahab kill 23 people and injure about 80.[9]

events.description: WikiLeaks starts  publishing the Guantanamo Bay files leak.
events.html: • 2011 – WikiLeaks starts publishing the Guantanamo Bay files leak.

events.description: A building collapses near Dhaka, Bangladesh, killing 1,134 people and injuring about 2,500 others.
events.html: • 2013 – A building collapses near Dhaka, Bangladesh, killing 1,134 people and injuring about 2,500 others.[10][11]

events.description: Violence in Bachu County, Kashgar Prefecture, of China's Xinjiang results in death of 21 people.
events.html: • 2013 – Violence in Bachu County, Kashgar Prefecture, of China's Xinjiang results in death of 21 people.
